#31: The piano cover of unravel by Animenz has much Rachmaninoff-like left hand arppegio and jumps, which gives it a majestic sound when needed. In addition, the entire piece is arranged like what Liszt would have written to show off his virtuosity; Liszt also likes to use grand arpeggios and jumps. It is nonetheless imperfect when considering the skill-aesthetic trade off. It can sound about the same even if the difficulty is cut substantially by taking out some of those jumps in the left hand. However, it must be acknowledged that it is an extremely sophisticated piece and the only sophisticated anime music cover I've ever heard so kudos to him. 😄

#37: The best known classical integer factorization algorithm, the General Number Field Sieve, factors an integer N roughly in exp(N^1/3) time. Shor's Algorithm can factor a given integer N roughly in (logN)^3 time (in other words, roughly polynomial time!!!!), but it requires a quantum computer to run. The largest integer factored using Shor's Algorithm to date is 21. :kekw:

#43: It is about time that I give the definition for ***bo*** as part of the Boboga Language. bo will from now on be a morphemic component of the Language that serves as a marker for affirmation('yes' or 'ok') when uttered with a flat inflection and serves as a marker for confusion/question when uttered with an upwards inflection ('huh?'). It will carry the meaning of what is equivalent to "I am not really paying attention to what you are talking about right now but I will respond anyways" in English. More definitions to come later C:

#44: Now we codify the definition for ***ga***. ga will be a morphemic component of the language that will not carry any meaning by itself but will only serve as a suffix to another semantic element. Let ga succeed some semantic element E with meaning M, then the string "E"+ "ga" will be used to convey that the situation which E describes has some interesting and (at least) mildly funny quality Q, which will be left to the interpreter as a mental exercise. For instance, if Trevor fails a water landing in minecraft and dies, and I say [some string] + "ga", a reasonable interpretation by Trevor of "ga" would be a playful mockery of some sort such as "holy shit u suck ass".

#45: Today we introduce a central feature of the Boboga Language -- let's call it stackability. Let `e` be a morphemic element of the language, then the ***n-stack*** of n repeatedly concatenated strings `ee...e` will convey the meaning of whatever `e` conveys, but with a magnified amplitude of expression as well as randomness and chaos, with the growth rate of such amplitudes with respect to `n` being an exponential decay such that the amplitudes quickly stagnate after a few strings being added to a stack. In addition, when `n` is an even number, arbitrary parts of the meaning of the `n-stack` gets reversed, which will again be left as a mental exercise for the interpreter. For an example, given the context of a casual conversation, "bobobo"  will carry roughly the meaning "Im not paying attention at all and I do not know what to say right now so I will say something random right now and hopefully we can come up with something else to say", but " bobobobo(!)" will carry roughly the meaning "this stuff is really interesting so let's talk more about this!! ❤️ ". #47: Since self-similar references are essential features of many human languages, Boboga will have one as well. ***ja*** will be the marker for infinite recursion in Boboga. It will take whatever morpheme M is before it, and transform into [M] + "ja".  For example, "bobo(ja)" is equivalent to "bobo(boja)" is equivalent to "bobo(boboja)" and so on.  Stackability was introduced to pave the way for this recursive feature of the language.  Since there is an infinite number of morphemes in a recursive phrase, the initializer of "ja" will determine whether the expressions is "even" or "odd". "boboja" will count as an even-number expression, while "boja" will count as an odd-number expression.  Right now, "ja" only serve as ***the*** superlative expression in Boboga, but more is to come!!
